Description: Today we're going to look at using Kubernetes as a defense in depth platfrom for AI agent systems. We're going to look at Hermes, an AI agent chat with tool calling ability, and see how that works security wise using K8s built in security mechanisms. They'll be considering the boundry between the reasoning layer (gateway) and the action layer (tool execution). We now dive in, and they lay out the issues - while LLMs have tool access with API keys and creds, how do we know they aren't being subverted with prompt injection or external input. Next up they get into the threat model, mapping out the attack surface. They point out many input points, like Slack, Discord and webhooks and any can contain malicious instructions. They talk about tool exec, credential leakage, and memory or skill vectors as part of the surface. We now look at Hermes, and the point out /opt/data is quite sensitive. Now we look at the defense - they start with basic things like least priv, moving on to K8s namespace layers which divides and isolates different parts of Hermes. They have a good text diagram, then do a short descrption of how it is set up. They then get into specific containers, noting the main interface is the gateway, and they harden this quite a bit. For /opt/data, they let the GW mount it rw, dashboard ro, and don't let it mount elsewhere. They go on to talk about network, tool-exec, MCP server perms, runtime policies, and how to handle output data. They talk about audits, how to handle skills, and much more. An excellent starting point to think about AI security.
