URL reference: https://nivelepsilon.com/2025/09/11/your-kubernetes-rollback-is-lying/
DateReviewed: 2026-05-18
Description: Today we'll be looking at rollbacks and their apparent flaws. We start with a story - a wayward deployment causing production to start failing, so we do our trusty thing and rollback; except that doesn't solve the issue; our monitors say okay, but things aren't working -- why? They explain that if your code made a DB change, then that change doesn't magically go away when you revert. They frame this as "time travel", and if your new rollout included changes outside of code, then those may reflect things your older code might choke on. They also explain that while your app may respond to a simple /health check, it may not be ready to serve actual requests in a broad way. Caches are cold, JITs are still jit-ting, and your customers are seeing slowness or timeouts. Their suggestion is using a startupProbe, to tell if your app is really ready. They also touch on traffic routing, and specifically how your mesh will route a lot of your traffic to the now warming pods, which may not be able to cope with it yet. They have good advice - with steps to follow - on how to recover, which may NOT involve a rollback. Figure out what is wrong, triage and evaluate the best way forward -- is it a hotfix, or jumping back to the last version? Very solid approach with good advice.
BottomLine: Very good piece on how to approach a failed deployment on Kubernetes
